{{infobox scholar | image = PSM V43 D594 Henry Carrington Bolton.jpg | caption = Engraving of head view of Henry Carrington Bolton, 1893 or 1900 | name = Henry Carrington Bolton | fullname = | birth_date = 29 January 1843<ref name=Boltonia1/> | birth_place = New York City<ref name=Boltonia2/> | death_date = {{death date and age|1903|11|19|1843|01|29|}} | death_place = | era = | region = | school_tradition = | main_interests = Chemistry; Scientific bibliography | notable_ideas = | major_works = ''Catalogue of Scientific and Technical Periodicals, 1665-1895'' | influences = <!-- possible: [[Jean Baptiste André Dumas]]; [[Charles Adolphe Wurtz]]; [[Robert Bunsen]]; [[Hermann Kopp]]; [[Gustav Kirchhoff]]; [[Friedrich Wöhler]]; [[August Wilhelm von Hofmann]] --> | influenced = }}
'''Henry Carrington Bolton''' (1843–1903) was an American chemist and bibliographer of science.
==Biography== He graduated from [[Columbia University|Columbia]] in 1862,<ref name=acab>{{Appletons'|wstitle=Bolton, Henry Carrington|year=1900|inline=1}}</ref> and then studied chemistry with [[Jean Baptiste André Dumas]] and [[Charles Adolphe Wurtz]] in Paris; with [[Robert Bunsen]], [[Hermann Kopp]], and [[Gustav Kirchhoff]] at [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]]; with [[Friedrich Wöhler]] at [[University of Göttingen|Göttingen]]; and with [[August Wilhelm von Hofmann]] in [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin]], and received a D. Phil. at Göttingen in 1866, for his work called “On the Fluorine Compounds of Uranium”.<ref name="Boltonia2">{{cite journal|last1=Pratt|first1=Herbert T. |title=Henry Carrington Bolton: A Truly Renaissance Man|journal=Boltonia |date=2004|volume=January |issue=6 |pages=2-5 |publisher=[[Chemical Heritage Foundation]] |url=http://www.chemheritage.org/Downloads/Library/Boltonia-06_2004.pdf|accessdate= 26 March 2018 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926001003/http://www.chemheritage.org/Downloads/Library/Boltonia-06_2004.pdf|archivedate=September 26, 2012|df=}} The rest of the issue is also about Bolton and his works.</ref>
After his graduation, he spent some years in travel. From 1872 until 1877, he was assistant in [[quantitative analysis (chemistry)|quantitative analysis]] in the Columbia School of Mines. In 1874 he was appointed professor of chemistry in the Woman's Medical College of the New York Infirmary. He resigned in 1877, when he became professor of chemistry and natural science in [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]]. The celebration of the centennial of chemistry at [[Northumberland, Pennsylvania]], the home of [[Joseph Priestley]], who discovered oxygen in 1774, was suggested and brought about by Bolton.<ref name=acab/>
Among his investigations, that of the action of organic acids on minerals is perhaps the most important, but most of his work was literary, and his private collection of early chemical books was unsurpassed in the United States.<ref name=acab/> Bolton published large bibliographies of chemistry and later of all scientific periodicals which are still used. He included [[alchemy]] in the chemistry listings and emphasized the continuity of the transition. He was a member of many scientific societies, perhaps more than any contemporary.<ref name="Boltonia1">{{cite journal|last1=Bohning|first1=J.J |title=In Memoriam: Henry Carrington Bolton, 29 January 1843 – 19 November 1903|journal=Boltonia |date=2004|volume=January |issue=6 |pages=1-2 |publisher=[[Chemical Heritage Foundation]] |url=http://www.chemheritage.org/Downloads/Library/Boltonia-06_2004.pdf|accessdate= 26 March 2018 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926001003/http://www.chemheritage.org/Downloads/Library/Boltonia-06_2004.pdf|archivedate=September 26, 2012|df=}} The rest of the issue is also about Bolton and his works.</ref>
The [[Science History Institute]] hosts the Bolton Society, which is named for H.C. Bolton, to support "printed materials devoted to chemistry and related sciences" and to support its Othmer Library of Chemical History.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bolton Society|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/bolton-society|website=Science History Institute|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>
== Works == * ''Catalog of Scientific and Technical Periodicals (1665–1882).'' 1885. * ''A Catalogue of Scientific and Technical Periodicals, 1665-1895.'' (second edition) 1897. Washington: Smithsonian Institution. Reprinted 1965 by Johnston Reprint Corporation. * {{cite book |last=Bolton |first=Henry Carrington | title = [[s:Evolution of the Thermometer|Evolution of the Thermometer, 1592-1743]] | year = 1900 | publisher = The Chemical Publishing Company | location = Easton, Pennsylvania | pages = 66&nbsp;– 79 }} * ''Select Bibliography of Chemistry (1492–1892)''. 1892. (lists 12,031 titles<ref name=Boltonia2/>) * ''Select Bibliography of Chemistry (1492–1904)''. (completed posthumously; lists over 14,000 titles) * ''The Follies of Science at the Court of [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor|Rudolph II]]''. 1904. Milwaukee: Pharmaceutical Review Publishing Company. ([http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-19466 Digital edition] by the [[University and State Library Düsseldorf]]) * {{cite book |editor-last=Bolton |editor-first=Henry Carrington |last=Priestly |first=Joseph | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nsUEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA98&dq=James+Keir+Priestley | title = Scientific Correspondence of Joseph Priestley |year=1892|location= Philadelphia|publisher= Collins Printing House}} * ''The Counting-Out Rhymes of Children: Their Antiquity, Origin, and Wide'' 1888
