'''Philippa Mein Smith''' is a New Zealand-Australian academic and historian who specialises in [[Australian history]], [[New Zealand history]], the [[history of Australia-New Zealand relations]] and [[health history]].
==Education== Mein Smith completed a Bachelor of Commerce degree at the [[University of Canterbury]] in 1977, and worked briefly as an accountant before returning to the university for a postgraduate study. She graduated with a Master of Arts degree in History in 1983.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.utas.edu.au/profiles/staff/humanities/philippa-mein-smith|title = Staff profile: Philippa Mein Smith|date = 22 December 2015|access-date = 9 February 2016|website = |publisher = University of Tasmania|last = |first = }}</ref> Her thesis was titled ''The State and Maternity in New Zealand.'' Mein Smith completed her Ph.D at the [[Australian National University]] in [[Canberra]], in 1990; her thesis was titled ''Reformers, Mothers and Babies.''<ref name=":0" />
==Career== From 1989 to 1992, Mein Smith was a lecturer in economic history at [[Flinders University]]. During this time she had a biography of her great-great-grandfather, [[William Mein Smith]], published in the ''[[Dictionary of New Zealand Biography]]''.<ref>{{DNZB|Mein Smith|Philippa|1s16|Smith, William Mein|9 February 2016||Philippa Mein Smith}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Wellington's founding fathers|url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/capital-life/8282937/Wellingtons-founding-fathers|newspaper = Stuff.co.nz|date = 2013-02-10|access-date = 2016-02-09|language = English|first = Kimberley|last = Rothwell}}</ref> She then moved to a position in the History Department at the University of Canterbury, where she remained for 21 years.<ref name=":0" />
From 2003 to 2006, Mein Smith was the recipient of a [[Royal Society of New Zealand]] Marsden Fund Grant, awarded to her to study the historical development of connections between Australia and New Zealand. This project was known as the "Anzac Neighbours" project. As a result, Mein Smith and her colleague [[Peter Hempenstall]] established the New Zealand Australia Connections Research Centre (NZAC) at the University of Canterbury in 2005.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url = http://www.comsdev.canterbury.ac.nz/chronicle/2008/ChronVol43-17.pdf|title = Chronicle, Vol. 43, No. 17|date = 24 October 2008|access-date = 9 February 2016|website = |publisher = University of Canterbury|last = |first = }}</ref>
In 2008 the centre was replaced with a larger New Zealand Australia Research Centre (NZARC), with Mein Smith as the director.<ref name=":1" /> Its launch coincided with the 25th anniversary of the New Zealand-Australia [[Closer Economic Relations]] Agreement (CER) and was marked with a symposium jointly hosted by the university and the New Zealand Institute of International Affairs.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dalziel: "Where to from here": Launch of NZAC {{!}} Scoop News|url = http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0810/S00242/dalziel-where-to-from-here-launch-of-nzac.htm|website = www.scoop.co.nz|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref>
In March 2013, Mein Smith took up a position as Professor of History at the [[University of Tasmania]].<ref name=":0" />
