{{Infobox archaeological culture |name = Songze Culture |map = Majiabang_map.svg |mapalt = |altnames = |horizon = |region = Eastern [[China]] |period = [[Neolithic China]] |dates = c. 3800 – c. 3300 BCE |typesite = |majorsites = |extra = |precededby = [[Majiabang culture]] |followedby = [[Liangzhu culture]] |module = {{Chinese |child = yes |t = 崧澤文化 |s = 崧泽文化 |p = Sōngzé wénhuà }} }}
[[File:Flickr - archer10 (Dennis) - DSCN8233BB.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Grey pottery wine vessel of the Songze culture, 3800~3200 BCE]] The '''Songze Culture''' was a [[Neolithic]] culture that existed between 3800 and 3300 BCE in the [[Lake Tai]] area near [[Shanghai]].{{sfnp|Wang|2001|p=220}}{{sfnp|Qin|2013|p=578}}
==Dates== Three radiocarbon dates were taken from Songze culture layers at Jiangli near [[Lake Tai]]. Two of the dates were obtained from charred rice grains, returning dates of 3360-3090 BCE and 3540-3370 BCE. The third date was taken from [[Polygonum aviculare|knotgrass]] and produced a date of 3660-3620 BCE.{{sfnp|Qiu et al.|2014}} Although it is accepted to be the successor of the [[Majiabang culture]], others have suggested that Songze was a successor phase to the [[Hemudu culture]].{{sfnp|Goodenough|1993|p=45}}
==Sites== ===Songze=== In 1957, archaeologists discovered a site north of Songze Village near Zhaoxiang Town {{zh|c=赵巷镇}} in Shanghai's [[Qingpu District, Shanghai|Qingpu District]].{{sfnp|Shanghai Qingpu Museum|2014}} Excavations have been conducted throughout 1961, 1974-1976, 1987, 1994-1995, and 2004. These revealed three cultural layers: the most recent had [[pottery]] from the [[Spring and Autumn period]]; the middle layer was a cemetery with 148 graves and numerous artefacts; the oldest layer belonged to a village of the [[Majiabang culture]].{{sfnp|Shanghai Qingpu Museum|2014}}
===Nanhebang=== 92 graves have been excavated from a Songze cemetery at Nanhebang.{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=134}}
===Pishan=== The Pishan cemetery contained 61 burials.{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=134}}
===Dongshan=== Dongshan Village is located near Jingang Town 18 km west of [[Zhangjiagang]]. It was discovered in 1989 and has undergone excavations by the [[Suzhou Museum]] (1989-1990), followed by two large [[Rescue archaeology|rescue excavations]] led by the [[Nanjing Museum]] in 2008-2009.{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=135}} The site is divided into three areas: area 1 was a small cemetery of 27 burials, all of which had different quantities of [[grave goods]], which has been used to suggest the existence of a [[Social_stratification#Anthropological_theories|stratified society]]; area 2 was a residential comprising five buildings in the centre of the site; area 3 was another burial ground in the site's west, with 10 tombs.{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=135}}
